{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489466"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"665"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/665"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.18,0.02,0.08,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114346"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/665"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-10-26T07:56:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T18:33:36+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-11-02T17:40:58+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-22 16:06:22"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"665"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"745"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96346"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16053"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47404"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96346"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114346"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is brought by her flatmates to the Emergency Department. She is in a distressed state, and is unable to give a coherent history. Her flatmates say she has a significant mental health history including bipolar disorder. They brought her known medications with them, which include lithium, escitalopram and the oral contraceptive pill. According to her friends, she has no other known medical conditions. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the last few hours she appears to have taken quite a few tablets of paracetamol and drunk four jugs of water. She has not had any recent head trauma. When she started vomiting, they decided to bring her to hospital. Her friends have not noticed any tremor or ataxia. They have not noticed any other changes in her behaviour before this, except that over the last few weeks she has been drinking more water than usual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is drowsy with a GCS of 6, blood pressure 120/70mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.0\u02daC. Nothing else abnormal is found on physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to clarify the clinical diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum biochemistry","Serum paracetamol","CT head","Blood sugar level","Serum lithium levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile all the options provided are reasonable investigations to be performed in this situation, the clue is in the history. Although the diagnosis is not certain, it is probable that this patient has water intoxication as a result of psychogenic polydipsia. Thus the \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum biochemistry\u003C/strong\u003E will provide a rapid answer if the problem is one of water intoxication, and will also assist with guiding treatment of the electrolyte abnormalities. It will also provide information on a broad set of differentials that will be more helpful than investigations with a high specificity as an initial test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWater intoxication/psychogenic polydipsia is a common presentation in patients with psychosis, bipolar disorder, personality disorders and incarcerated patients. It may be a symptom of psychosis, or may be a side effect of any medication that either increases thirst or causes a dry mouth through anti-cholinergic effects. So lithium, olanzapine, benztropine, selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) and tricyclic antidepressants (TCAs) could be contributors to this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELithium toxicity usually presents with tremor, ataxia, and altered consciousness. Lithium toxicity is more likely in the setting of dehydration or renal impairment, rather than excessive water intake.\u00a0This patient\u0027s recent excessive water intake could have been triggered by lithium toxicity (lithium toxicity can also cause arginine vasopressin resistance [AVP-R] previously known as nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, leading to polyuria and then subsequent polydipsia). Whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Elithium levels\u003C/strong\u003E should be done, this is not as urgent as serum electrolytes. However, in this case it is more likely that her lithium levels will be low because of water intoxication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical presentation is unlikely to be explained by paracetamol toxicity. In a paracetamol overdose, the patient is unlikely to experience a change in consciousness, and are usually asymptomatic. In severe cases, patients may experience nausea, vomiting, and signs of hepatic toxicity. Thus, while \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum paracetamol\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed it is not the investigation that is most likely to clarify the cause of the patient\u0027s symptoms and signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has no history of diabetes mellitus. Although it is possible that her presentation may be a first presentation of diabetes mellitus with an altered mental state, this is not as likely as water intoxication, and thus, while \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood sugar levels\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed they are not the most likely investigation to clarify the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient has no history of head trauma or significant medical history, a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT head\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be beneficial at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Water intoxication can be caused by psychogenic polydipsia and may present with altered consciousness.","Psychogenic polydipsia can occur in patients on psychiatric medications that cause dry mouth or increase thirst.","Broad initial investigations will better inform differential diagnoses than more specific investigations."],"references":["Peechakara BV, Gupta M. Water Toxicity. [Updated 2020 Jul 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537231/","Dundas B, Harris M, Narasimhan M. Psychogenic polydipsia review: etiology, differential, and treatment. Curr Psychiatry Rep. 2007 Jun;9(3):236-41. doi: 10.1007/s11920-007-0025-7. PMID: 17521521."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96346"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"665"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96346"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T18:33:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T18:34:01+09:30","number":8,"notes":"User feedback noted; we have acknowledged potential for AVP-R  (nephrogenic DI) but distinguishing this from PP in practice is nuanced (e.g., copeptin levels/water deprivation tests etc.) and ultimately, best answer remains serum EUC","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-09-15T18:33:37+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-665-8.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T184737Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=9776d15b09d3c05e941c974000b8a2ce9307e2a849f71ce13d81058c399f489b"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"665"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114346"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"745"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/188"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Psychotic disorders","